<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-686-398  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 686 398.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Design  August 24 1989 v37 n18 p19(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Photosensor circuit sprouts atop optical fiber. (University ofMichigan, Ann Arbor research)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gunn, Lisa.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Researchers at the University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, created anopto-electronic device that provides a direct conversion offiber-optic signals to electrical current.andP;  The device combinesthe speed and compactness of optical fiber with the switching andamplification features of electric circuits.andP;  Using molecular-beamepitaxy, a thin film of gallium arsenide (GaAs) is grown oneatomic layer at a time onto a glass fiber capable of transmittingdata with light pulses.andP;  This GaAs photoconductor then translatesthe light into weak electric signals which are amplified by asmall transistor attached to the device.andP;  A direct conversion fromfiber-optic signals to electrical current is the result.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber opticsGallium arsenide semiconductorsResearch and DevelopmentMichigan, University ofOptoelectronic devicesThin Films.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>